# Design Patterns and Code Organization

## File Size Limit: 150 Lines Maximum

Every source file must contain **at most 150 lines of code**.

- Enforces Single Responsibility and keeps files navigable.
- When a file grows toward the limit, split before adding more.
- **Splitting strategies**: Extract interfaces to `*.interface.ts` or `types.ts`; move helpers to `*.utils.ts`; split a class into a base in one file and concrete impl in another; one pattern/feature per file.

## Pattern Selection

| Pattern                     | Use When                                                          | Avoid When                     |
| --------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **State**                   | Behavior varies by internal state; replacing switch/case on state | Simple flags; few states       |
| **Strategy**                | Interchangeable algorithms at runtime                             | Single algorithm               |
| **Chain of Responsibility** | Multiple handlers may process a request; dynamic chains           | Single handler; fixed flow     |
| **Builder**                 | Complex object, many optional parts, step-by-step construction    | Simple objects; few params     |
| **Observer**                | Multiple listeners for the same events                            | Single consumer                |
| **Decorator**               | Add/stack behaviors dynamically (retry, log, cache)               | Static, single behavior        |
| **Factory Method**          | Creation delegated to callers; varying product types              | One product type; simple `new` |

## State vs Strategy

- **State**: Context has a _current state_; state object handles requests and may _transition_ context to another state. Use for stage machines, wizards, workflows (e.g. discovery → requirements → design).
- **Strategy**: Context delegates an _algorithm_ to a strategy; no notion of "current state" or transitions. Use for swapping sort/search/format logic.

## Chain of Responsibility vs Decorator

- **Chain**: Request passes along a chain until one handler handles it (or none). Handlers can be reordered; each handles or forwards. Use for validation, auth, middleware pipelines.
- **Decorator**: Wrap one component; all wrappers see every request. Use for adding retry, logging, caching around a single execution path.

## TypeScript Conventions

- Prefer **interfaces** for public contracts; use **abstract classes** only when you need shared implementation for the pattern (e.g. base handler, base state).
- Keep pattern types in `src/lib/patterns/<pattern>/` (e.g. `state/state.interface.ts`, `chain/handler.interface.ts`).
- Export from `index.ts` per subfolder; main entry at `src/lib/patterns/index.ts`.

## Builder Pattern

Use for complex config/context objects. Fluent API, return `this` from setters.

```typescript
// Good: fluent builder, under 150 lines
class RequirementContextBuilder {
  private data: Partial<RequirementContext> = {};
  withProjectBrief(brief: ProjectBrief): this {
    this.data.projectBrief = brief;
    return this;
  }
  withActors(actors: Actor[]): this {
    this.data.actors = actors;
    return this;
  }
  build(): RequirementContext {
    return { ...defaults, ...this.data } as RequirementContext;
  }
}
```

## Observer Pattern

Use for agent/stage events when multiple listeners are needed (logging, metrics, UI). Subject holds observers and calls `update()` (or specific methods) on notify.

```typescript
// Subject: attach/detach/notify; Observer: update(subject)
interface AgentObserver {
  onStageChange?(stage: string, ctx: unknown): void;
  onToolExecution?(tool: string, result: unknown): void;
}
```

## File Layout for Patterns

Keep each file under 150 lines by splitting by role:

```
src/lib/patterns/
  state/
    index.ts
    state.interface.ts
    base-state.ts
  chain/
    index.ts
    handler.interface.ts
    abstract-handler.ts
```

Reference: [Refactoring.Guru – Design Patterns in TypeScript](https://refactoring.guru/design-patterns/typescript).
